<HEADLINE>
<P>
WRITING FOR CREDIT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Brian Grazer's stunningly arrogant comment regarding "roundtable" 
screenwriting -- "If a script is good, what does it matter how many people 
wrote it?" -- is typical of the contempt in which Hollywood studio types hold 
writers, brought about by the long and continuing ineffectiveness of the 
Writers Guild of America West ("Roundtable Writing: A Headache for Guild," Feb. 
9). 
</P>
<P>
 Right, Brian.What does it matter who wrote "The Three Sisters"? Or "The Glass 
Menagerie"? Or "All About Eve"? 
</P>
<P>
 I would like to humbly suggest that you "roundtable" the producers and 
directors of your next movie. And I further suggest, since it doesn't matter 
who gets credit for what in films, that you restrict your credit to one among a 
dozen or so others (who probably had more to do with the actual making of the 
movie than you) in a credit roll at the end of the film. 
</P>
<P>
 See how much you like that roundtable. 
</P>
<P>
 GARRY SHEPPARDI 
</P>
<P>
 North Hollywood 
</P>
</TEXT>
