<TEXT>
<P>
 GOING MODERN: The headquarters for the Armed Forces Radio and Television 
Network must be a Manhattan or Hollywood high-rise. Wrong! Believe it or not, 
the network broadcasts from Sun Valley in a building originally built as a bank 
computer center.. . . The network, which reaches 1.3 million military personnel 
in 128 countries, plays more Christian rock and fewer Bible services these 
days, and the soldiers like it.(B13) 
</P>
<P>
 SCHOOL LOYALTY: They said they might bail, but the overwhelming majority of 
CalArts students are sticking with the earthquake-ravaged campus. Friday was 
the last day students could withdraw and receive a full refund, but only about 
80 of the 964 left.. . . The school estimates $2 million in bills for satellite 
classrooms and lost tuition. (B20) 
</P>
<P>
 BUMMED BOWLER: Pity Paul Hagerty. Rocket Bowl in Chatsworth, his weekly 
hangout for 14 years, won't reopen till early March because of earthquake 
damage, sending his mood straight into the gutter. "I miss it," he complained. 
"This is my home away from home. Other places charge too much money.". . . 
Besides, many (above) remain closed or overcrowded. (C14) 
</P>
<P>
 MODEL QB: Palmdale High's Rocque Sandoval, who has overcome far more than 
intimidating pass rushers, might find ex-Raider Jim Plunkett a perfect role 
model. Plunkett's parents were blind, yet he became a great player who took his 
team to two Super Bowl titles. . . . Sandoval's parents are deaf, but that 
hasn't stopped him from throwing touchdowns and picking up plenty of support 
from home. (C14) 
</P>
<P>
 EVERYTHING COUNTS: Don't call tonight's taping of "The Jackson Family Honors" 
in Las Vegas a strictly charity event; much of the dough goes to cover 
expenses. (F1) . . . But at least one Valley group, the Permanent Charities 
Committee of the Entertainment Industry in Studio City, will send some money 
raised to quake victims. Michael Arkush 
</P>
