<P>
PAC BELL: BUZZ THROUGH OR BUZZ OFF 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Bloomberg Business News 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 For the person who only wants to talk to some of the people some of the time, 
Pacific Bell has introduced a call-blocking service called "Do Not Disturb." 
</P>
<P>
 The service allows customers to block calls from people who don't know a 
prearranged four-letter password.If callers know the password, the call goes 
through. If not, they're told to call back later or leave a message at the 
beep. 
</P>
<P>
 "Participants use their home phones to change their password and turn the 
service on or off just as often as they like," said Jennifer Brunn of Pacific 
Bell. 
</P>
<P>
 The company is currently letting about 200 customers in Southern California 
try the service out for free as part of a trial. If the trial goes as expected, 
Pacific Bell plans to offer "Do Not Disturb" for about $3.50 to $4.00 a month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
